Battle to the last blood: MP3 players against mobile phones
We will advise how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
This makes it clear that it is better to buy only the phone.
Nevertheless, there are many reasons why you should get an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the needs of the future owner.
Perhaps you would hardly buy an expensive high-quality turntable to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
First of all, these musical products do not come out as LP and from a qualitative point of view for this reason there is not even an objective reason.
But if your shelves are full of hard-rock, jazz or blues vinyl, you probably dream of a turntable like this.
It also works with portable music, i.e. compressed music or simply in MP3 format.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend for a reader 8 thousand crowns, just as a fan of Pink Floyd perhaps hardly digests the headphones from twenty crowns of the market.
Two extremes between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It is up to you to decide the battery life.
Some high-quality music players manage to do much more than just read music, which, however, does not make mobile phones even by mistake.
There is no other current device as universal as the mobile phone.
Next to the primary functions, call and send sms, can read music and videos, record both and has a camera, sometimes better sometimes worse and maybe even can navigate.
And if we take into account smartphones and palms you will also have a miniature computer in your pocket.
It is a small miracle because no refrigerator can do the grill and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of the mobile phone also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile phone and the earlier the indicator on the screen will require the charger.
Reading music consumes a lot of energy.
Few cell phones can read music for more than twelve hours, usually, and much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simplest ones) are much more effective.
As for cheap mobile phones, don’t count on them to last for more than a few hours.
If you still add us, from time to time, some calls, get yourself to work for safety another charger, this also applies to the most expensive appliances.
But you won’t have this problem with an MP3 player, even the worst ones last at least 9 hours at continuous functionality with a charge.
There is another problem when downloading music to your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB port and not all of them can be connected to the computer without special software.
Certainly the music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few memory players are able to do it without an adapter for minicards that are not used in mobile phones.
Readers, except for some exceptions (Ipods) do not need any special software.
Simply fill the device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and readers create themselves a multimedia library ordered according to the names of the performers, the name of the album, genre or according to the user's classification.
Some devices only play the folder tree structure, similar to the Explorer tool in Windows, and some know how to do both things (river, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobile phones can do more.
When choosing a particular device, pay particular attention to the battery resistance, memory capacity, quality and type of audio outputs and clearly the ease of use.
If you need music mainly from the background and if you listen to it every day only briefly on the tram you just need a mobile phone that reads MP3.
This is now possible, clearly on any mobile phone.
You don’t have to worry too much about what formats your phone or reader recognizes.
MP3 players support them all, the global majority of the music that comes to you will be just in this format.
In addition to this format that belongs to the most common ones, the total majority of devices support music in WMA format.
There is less AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods).
The best mobile phones also allow, for example, to buy music online.
Just visit, through the mobile internet, the corresponding pages of the operator (or another provider) and buy the song or album.
This same service could already be a valid topic to buy a mobile-reader.
Unfortunately, the offer of the operators is poor and is usually limited only to the hit of the radio moment.
The prices are not very low.
But it is generally assumed that this mode of selling music (either via GSM, internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their phones behind them.
Anyone who wants to listen to something frowns in their pocket while the MP3 player is forgotten at home.
But it also depends on this, if you always carry behind the headphones or at least the wireless headset.
If not, you can use the built-in player that almost every mobile phone, but only a small portion of MP3 players, has.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of mobile-readers will be, for many, the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3,000 crowns.
For 3 and 4 thousand crowns you will already buy a very dignified walkman.
Usually, however, you will be limited by the absence of an entrance for the common headphones.
The best and technically most equipped mobile phones and also with the 3.5 mm socket for common headphones, cost up to 15 thousand crowns.
Instead, the advantage of readers is, in addition to others, easy handling.
The simplest ones are not necessarily cheaper (see our choice) anyone can really handle them.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of the handling once with the common stereo or perhaps the turntable, is obvious.
There is no danger of accidentally impacting the launch of the mobile internet network and as a result of a giant bill for the transmission of data.
What equipment to take
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Also with regard to the purchase of the respective card, which is included in the 2,000 crowns.
But be careful.
The base models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones do it even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, take Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to spend more than 1 100 crowns.
If you are among the most demanding listeners, preferably take specialized phones - walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have individual keys for MP3 and the convenience of the service so it comes close to the same MP3 player.
In this area, Sony Ericsson has made more strides, which phones of the walkman line have the same scale of use as MP3 players sold separately.
The MP3 players of the above brands provide you with the same service and the same price category up to 4,000 crowns, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery resistance (commonly 15 hours, usually up to 35 hours).
The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic as early as this year.
Maybe.
Perhaps the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all services like their partners in Western Europe.
However, something is missing here – a virtual operator that obliges traditional operators to lower the price.
Maybe it won't be long.
The fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive ones in Europe we have already written many times on Mobil.cz.
At the end of the day, <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> also confirmed this, noting that the price of SMS is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the European Commission’s latest steps in the field of regularisation of roaming charges, perhaps a paradoxical situation will arise – for some Czech mobile phone customers, SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to start the fight.
Maybe it sounds absurd, but here we have three mobile networks and coverage high above 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense he often emphasizes also the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, who in the past has sometimes expressed that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network probably no longer has many possibilities. (Otherwise it may be difficult to find other frequencies by now.)
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry into the market of virtual operators that has led to a significant drop in prices, to which traditional operators would then have to react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile into the market, similar voices sounded in Britain as we do.
However, it has been shown that there is a place for such operators and that they can be really successful.
At the end of the day, we don’t have to go very far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year this operator managed to win more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time, Mobilking is behind the Penta financial group to which the Czech Republic belongs, among other things, U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to be able to work effectively, it is enough to have far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not entail, that is to say, relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually come at low cost, offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the narrowest range of services.
So for example Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS that cost at least half compared to its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows can be a pretty good move even betting on a target group not too long ago.
This operator aims, so to speak, specifically at men.
“Real men choose Mobilking operator they like and can be trusted,” says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can also assert a similar concept as in Poland.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of services, it is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic no possibility, mobile network operators say
But it seems almost certain that if there will ever be an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not have many expectations.
Mobilking will be lit rather in other countries in our area," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, the press spokesman for the financial group Penta, told Mobile.cz.
Thus, it indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are not very supportive of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything because you do not create any potential competitor.
For some time now he has not hidden his interest in starting a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group that would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And the sooner you do better, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile network operators.
We have already made progress in the negotiations with some of them," said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe better times will come.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator will probably have it by the end of the year.
For now, however, an impenetrable wall of silence stands around its creation.
"At the moment we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has addressed us," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of the press section of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nika O2 mentioned in his statement to Mobil.cz.
The specificity of the Czech market is also used by other operators.
T-Mobil spokesman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> added in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "For now we have not noticed any commercial project that is vital and beneficial for both, on which it is possible to continue to build."
“On the T-Mobile network, a virtual operator will hardly appear before the end of the year.
At this point we have already had to have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon.”
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on achieving its own 3G license requests.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
We consider this, from the point of view of customers, the most producer.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common fast mobile internet network.”
The competent authorities -with the complicit operators
The attitude of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in profit.
Why, then, facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The annoyances around U:fon creation testify that when operators care about something they know how to row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure pressed <0xC4><0x8C>TU in the period of creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by the information of public access from the web pages of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
But right now U:fon serves as a topic for which not to accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> noted: “The competitive environment of the mobile phone market has been little more than enhanced with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would place high demands on him and above all on his services.
However, the attitude of mobile operators is quite surprising the complete disinterest on the part of the Czech regulatory bodies.
It is not just the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> that unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Great Britain and other developed countries - has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, has taken its typical position in relation to the whole problem.
“The virtual operator’s entry into the mobile phone market would be possible after the conclusion of the necessary infrastructure lease contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator has been completed.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers has probably not been interesting enough for traditional operators," said Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa, of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS external relations section, in response to our question.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators may come as no surprise.
On the other hand, it is more than a delicate matter on the part of the office that has to defend the interests of consumers and also to take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market.
Especially when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: “Outside where virtual operators commonly operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile telephony services.”
But obviously the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Truly shocking in the whole situation is the almost emotional harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence, it arises on its own.
Just as the same price of petrol for all petrol stations is certainly the result of coincidence and competition.
"The section found no signs of anti-competitive behavior regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so it does not have a corresponding greater responsibility for its behaviour in the market.
The necessary tools for the opening of the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be missing from the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many controversial points.
Of course, there is the analysis of the relevant markets elaborated by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of economic competition the only market.
In such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - for the creation of a virtual operator is always necessary the agreement of the operator of the network.
And the mobile operator has – logically, at the end of the day – the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we do not admit this argument, for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS it should be a minimum warning that three mobile operators proceed in such a strange way.
At the same time, the complaints from stakeholders (including the aforementioned GTS Novera company) show that during negotiations with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
Downloading responsibility to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which <0xC3><0x9A>OHS keeps itself out of the whole thing.
We have already seen this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to promote the expansion of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>’s rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recently approved update of the telecommunications law, despite the fact that many experts expected the situation to improve.
The representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS need to know this more than well, but perhaps their interests lie elsewhere.
You can do it when no one is watching.
While without realizing it remains the operation of such pseudo-virtual operators, of which there are even some in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their price lists of mobile services, but they are only partially public.
These are usually companies that deal with multi-level marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only pre-established people.
The magic lies in the fact that the company appears to the operator as a classic corporate customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer you then receive special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the trading conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a pre-sale.
"If you present the cases you are talking about, which we will be interested in, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions, and could lead to the conclusion of cooperation with this company," said Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1>.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity would reach the ears of the subjects responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the cases of the 3 mentioned companies, there may be thousands of customers.
No operator defends itself at the same time from such an attitude.
From the activity of these companies they derive a not indifferent profit and at the same time - unlike real virtual operators - they are not damaged in any way with their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns of possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculations, however, only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it as the usual customers of mobile phone operators."
But this is exactly what should be a little strange to <0xC4><0x8C>TU.
In addition, another question opens for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has rights strong enough to expose similar activities and if it does not want you will not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators who have no idea of all this and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we won't be more expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile phone market has led to a significant drop in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all the countries where operators were born, traditional operators more or less tried to prevent their creation.
The topics they used were pretty much the same – too small a market, too saturated a limit, problems with the quality of services, etc.
But in the developed countries in these cases, the regulatory bodies have intervened to defend not the mobile operators but their customers.
Both with the formal measures and with the non-formal pressure, then we came to the creation of the first virtual operator and he was joined by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies throw themselves from one to the other the whole case like a boiling potato.
In our experience, we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases makes him more than comfortable.
But let's not throw away the sponge.
If the background information is correct and the virtual operator will appear really soon from us, the Czech mobile market will get back on its feet.
If one of the operators had consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, only <0xC3><0x9A>OHS could hardly remain impassive to the rejection (discrimination) of the other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
