Michele de Milly, a spokeswoman for Avalon Bay, said that while the company wants to use the road, it doesn’t necessarily mean it wants to own it.
“The main concern of Avalon Bay is to renew this derelict alley and turn it into a public amenity,” he said, adding that the city has suggested the sale.
Seth Donlin, a Housing Preservation spokesman, said it was in fact the city's desire to sell the road and noted that the agency's purpose was to develop the property rather than administer it.
Compared to its more colorful neighbor, Bowery, Extra Place left a slight historical imprint.
Some believe that it took its name in 1802, when a large farm owned by Philip Minthorne was divided among his numerous children and the narrow strip of land was not reclaimed.
The back door to CBGB, the punk rock monument that closed in 2006, opened on Extra Place, and the road is perhaps best known as the set for the cover photo of the Ramones album "Rocket to Russia."
"The ground was beautiful," said Danny Fields, the Ramones' manager, who took the photo in November 1976.
"It was filled with garbage, clothes and bits of barrels, posters, leaves, ropes."
Some residents, including some bloggers who write of East Village "gentrification," have opposed the idea of selling Extra Place, arguing that the publicly owned piece, modest as it is, should remain public.
Others praised Extra Place as a rarity – a fragment of the city almost completely changed that should be left alone.
Jeremiah Moss, who has a blog called Jeremiah's Vanishing New York (subtitled, "The Book of Complaints: A Little Nostalgic Look at the Dying City"), published part of a City History Discourse that appeared on The New Yorker in 1952.
The author, Brendan Gill, wrote: "Extra Place is a narrow alley with no exit, dark even by day and bounded warehouse doors in rusty iron and windows with sardines, with old weekly newspapers fluttering along the lowlands."
With few exceptions, the road seemed almost the same as a recent night.
A rat ran smoothly through the back of the street near a door leading inside the CBGB, which is now the site of an aristocratic clothing store.
On the walls were graffiti and a 22-ounce empty beer bottle lying near a group of fresh abandoned newspapers.
Few passers-by said they rarely thought of Extra Place but suggest it would need to be a little embellished.
Mr. Fields, for his part, said he also thinks some people underestimate the attraction of the road in its current state.
“The best years of my life,” he said, “were in black, dirty, disgusting places.”
The Bilingual Debate: Immersion in English
In this episode of Educational Look, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the candidates’ position on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, a senior fellow in California studies and the senior director of educational studies at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of the book “Not Good As You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs to Choose a School.”
Attracting Hispanic voters is a complicated business.
Barack Obama’s education projects are a significant example.
Mr. Obama’s campaign notes that, “African-American and Latino students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students,” which is true.
To combat these shortcomings in achieving the goals, Obama’s education plan specifically supports, among other things, “transitional bilingual education” for English students.
Yet the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes classroom teaching in languages other than English, does not take into account his interest in bridging learning gaps.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles County.
The students of the school are mostly Hispanic and low-income.
More than a third of students, many of whom have recently arrived, are studying English.
But, among fourth graders, an astonishing 100 percent of students took the upper-level test in the 2008 math state exam.
An equally surprising 93 percent of fourth graders took the expert-level test on the art-of-language-English.
This incredible result was achieved using a different ingredient than Mr. Obama’s favorite.
Sixth Street emphasizes review and exercise, constant assessment of skills and an attitude of the "no excuses" type.
In addition, and this is where Mr. Obama should take note, according to Linda Mikels, director of Sixth Street, the school’s obstructive approach to English students is “full immersion.”
The use of English emphasizes the almost exclusive use of English in the context of education.
Mrs. Mikels, who opposes bilingual education, told me, “We had a fantastic success with a student just coming from Mexico and if you had entered the class 12 months later you wouldn’t have been able to pinpoint which one it was.”
"It works," he noted, "for us it works."
Would Obama model a school like Sixth Street Prep to replicate it in other Hispanic-majority schools and with English students?
The results achieved by the school make the answer to that question very easy, but the educational policy in his own party (the National Education Associations is a longtime supporter of bilingual education) and his own continued support for bilingual education prevent him from predicting Mr. Obama's answer.
While he agrees that immigrants should study English, Obama recently made the argument banal when he said that people should stop worrying about “only-English” legislation.
Instead, he said, "you have to make sure that your children are able to speak Spanish."
If Obama really wants to close these achievement gaps, he should carefully consider educational models that work rather than disparaging or trivializing them.
