In a city apart, pride and processes of a black life
Hidden in the extensive theme park in the suburbs of Orlando, a few miles from the splendour, the noise, the huge, lies the quiet city where the pride and complications of the African-American experience enter life.
Eatonville, the first all-black city incorporated into the country and Zora's birthplace, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet fields, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools and no prison."
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to show their respect to Hurston, Harlem Renaissance’s most famous writer.
Yet in many ways, the city that he described—and that stops tourists understanding it in the Florida tourist guide produced by the Depression-era Federal Writers’ Project—remains a place apart.
It is so independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with the white man, who “knowing so little of us, doesn’t know what’s being lost.”
Even now, in a year where a black presidential nominee, Senator Barack Obama, has been called for an opening address on race, many here remain wary of the outsider’s look.
“We are very cautious about how our story is told,” said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city’s oldest church.
"It must be fair."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and difficulty.
It is both a historical model of black empowerment and a community of nearly 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a literary center but also an example in the shadow of the oaks of the rural black culture of the South - sometimes disdainful, sometimes rewarded - born of American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the residents here are both proud and protective.
And the concern for Eatonville's image really began with Zora, who everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown through sincere, dialect-rich books such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of Florida’s guide turned the city, just off Route 17, a road that runs through Florida’s often-forgotten center into a scenario of black history and human drama.
Low as a crane in both life and literature, Hurston took readers to the shop owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then detoured to more private areas.
"Out of the street to the left," he wrote, "is the modern public school, brown with white finishes, with its well-maintained gardens and courtyards, which Howard Miller always looked after, thinking he could barely read and write."
She also mentioned the widow's new husband Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and whatever suits the passage rooms".
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
Clearly, this was not Fodor's.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
“Zora was saying it like it was,” said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson’s girls who Hurston immortalizes by citing men singing coarse songs about their beauty.
He adds: "Some people don't like it."
Hurston is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who frequently returned from her family moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalls that when Hurston was in town, he usually arrived without warning in a triumphant Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still boasts decent clothing.
Many inhabitants were fascinated, says Mr. Franklin, while others sighed.
“People were always very happy to see Zora,” Mr. Franklin said.
But, he added, leaning on his back patio chair over Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books had gone out of print.
Along with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a star of literature, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
In Eatonville, there were no major memorial ceremonies, and no major conferences.
"I don't think they understand his contribution to the world or his legacy to everyone," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
A change occurred in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to place a five-lane highway across the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the main two-lane road.
Orlando's expansion has already pushed Interstate 4 across the city's western boundary.
The proposal came as Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had ended the idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the battle over racial mixing brought hatred to the community’s doorstep.
“During that time, a group of white boys came and threw oranges and things at people sitting on one side,” says Mr. Franklin.
“In fact, we had a girl who was killed by that one time.
They threw a coconut tree out of a car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston made a request to the Supreme Court for forced integration, calling his Brown decision against the school office "an insult rather than an honor to my race".
Residents now say that school desegregation, despite being positive in some respects, dilutes Eatonville’s cohesion and jeopardizes the confidence of its youth.
“Black kids were used to being hugged — I remember this — you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening,” said N. Y. Nathri, the daughter of Ella Dinkins and the executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a non-profit group.
This lasted, he added, until teachers and students came from the same place.
"You didn't embrace your white teacher because your white teacher -- I mean, there's a cultural divide there," Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped and created space for many more Zora Neale Hurstons - black writer, actress and artist who overcame prejudices, as she did, with cheerful self-confidence and lines like: "How can some deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I just don't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker began a long journey to the unmarked tomb of Hurston and began fighting for the resurrection of her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Robert E. Hemenway's Hurston hit the bookshelves, reintroducing it into the American canon.
The highway project came just as his most famous daughter had once again turned on the lights of the overpass.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a lifesaver.
The community began designing a festival dedicated to Hurston in 1988 to show what could ruin the state with its highway.
Thousands of fans came to the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the commemoration.
Many years later, the state pulled back from its road project.
“The five lanes of the resurrected highway have brought what would be called high speed, a real pride for the city,” Ms. Nathiri said.
Mrs. Boyd puts it more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project helped change the city’s self-image.
Outsiders like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started coming to church here in 1993, began to appear in large numbers, and residents began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the public historical register in 1998.
A new one-story bookstore (named Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a re-paved and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can give the feeling of a side street under the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1980s.
(It's 90 percent black today.)
Outsiders who come to look for Eatonville’s story, for its meaning, are often still treated with caution.
A permit requested in advance is required for most of the interviews, to some things – such as the murals on Eatonville’s oldest church, painted by a white man, showing black men in the fields – they are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Ms. Jones, a fat teacher, with a weakness for bright red, still fear that their island community will be misunderstood.
Yet, as soon as the Hurston festival expanded, a high level of civic pride also emerged.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville with Hurston seeing his entire race: beautiful, trouble and everything, no better, no worse and proud, creative, great worker, stupid and confused like other races and ethnic groups in America.
It is sincere civic affection that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s grandson, Edwin Harvey, 18, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the local government or for the Police Department, which he said may need help.
And even those who are younger, such as Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
“A lot of people, if they just walked in here, will think, ‘Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,’” Alondra Kenon said after Mass on a recent Sunday.
“But if you really stop and take a moment to look at history, it’s really a pretty city.”
Here in New York we all speak fluently of finance
On the surface, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newspaper stalls and the huge television screens of Times Square, they wouldn’t notice they were in the eye of the storm.
They would never guess that glass offices, honeycombs over their heads bankers and hedge fund managers who monopolize New York City live every day the worst “bad day in the office” since the 1929 collapse.
Factories shake metal carts for tea through sidewalks, carrying muffin trays for breakfast meetings.
Latin Americans drag their feet between condominiums carrying, like human mules, 50 and broken ironed shirts hanging from a stick on their shoulders.
Employees are still waiting in line for their morning bagel at the food carts on the sidewalks, and it is still impossible to take a yellow taxi between 16 and 19 on a working day.
It didn’t seem like there was a real crisis, until, with all the talk of ruin and sadness, I decided to open a new savings book on Thursday afternoon.
Although I had planned the matter so that it coincided with the late afternoon break at my JP Morgan Chase branch, a queue of about twenty was already waiting in line.
Not in front of the cashier's counter, to withdraw money or make deposits, but in front of the customer service counter, where old customers order checkbooks, tourists ask directions for the Macy's department store and new customers open accounts.
Many of those in front of me, I would have learned later from Starr, my “trust banker,” were in line for my own reason.
Unlike me, however, they have already taken the savings from the smaller banks from the places from which they make the commuters, such as those from New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
They took the money from so-called thrifts (a bit like a construction company), credit unions, and types of city savings banks whose subsidiaries operate only within a state, and they say they treat customers like family.
In the past few years, 15 of these banks have gone bankrupt.
In recent days the Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, has been subjected to controlled administration, and, as New Yorkers headed home for the weekend on a Friday afternoon, another bank, Wachovia, with savings deposits of $440 billion, was looking for a buyer who saved her.
The clerks and clerks who stood before me, afraid of another collapse, were moving their money to a bank perceived as a safe harbor, the bank that is asking for more bail on Wall Street.
The common New Yorkers in recent weeks have become competent in finance.
A woman at my trusted Chinese supermarket, speaking on the phone, referred to Lehman Brothers, the bankrupt bank, and its emaciated CEO Dick Fuld in all familiarity, as if complaining about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed gatekeeper, almost fifty years old in my condo, has changed the subject from our normal conversation topic about Brad and Angelina or the delivery of my groceries.
She told me, after my visit to the bank, "Now I have all my savings in market funds!.
I’ve changed, I’m not taking any risks.”
Desecrated Muslim graves as Austria turns right.
Heinz-Christian Strache, to the left of the Austrian right wing of the Freedom Party and Filip Dewinter of the Belgian right-wing party Vlaams Belang, take part in a demonstration to present the organization "Cities against Islamization" in Antwerp, Thursday, January 17, 2008.
They carry road signs like those representing mosques with a red line passing in the middle.
Police blamed right-wing extremists for desecrating a Muslim cemetery in Austria, the same week that far-right political parties made a lot of money in national general elections.
More than 90 graves were severely damaged at the Traun cemetery, near Linz, sometime between Friday night and this morning, in what police believe was an organized action.
The culprits spray-painted Jewish symbols like the Star of David over some graves, but the detectives believe it may have been an attempt to mask extremist motivations driven by a hatred for Muslim immigrants.
It is not clear if the incident is somehow related to the election.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were “deeply shocked” by the news of the desecration, which took place towards the end of Ramadan, a month of religious significance for Muslims.
Austria, meanwhile, embarked on a spiritual quest following its turn to the right in yesterday's parliamentary elections.
The two far-right parties that took nearly 30 percent of the vote, the Austrian Freedom Party and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, have campaigned with vehemently anti-immigration tickets and some of their slogans have been defined by xenophobic critics.
Heinz-Christian Strache, the leader of the Freedom Party who won more than 18 percent of the vote, campaigned against veils and burqas and also voiced his opposition to foods that are perceived as connected to Islam.
At the final meeting in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" to prevent the growth of Islam.
Both parties appear to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, citing them as political symbols of a continued Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analyses made immediately after the election, which established the far right as the nation’s strongest political bloc, indicated that the change was brought mostly by young voters who are concerned about their future in the European Union.
