Relapsed drivers of alcoholism will have to install the "alcolock"
The Ministry of Interior requires that drivers with three administrative sanctions for excessive alcohol in the blood, install in his car the system that prevents driving the vehicle in a state of intoxication or if it does not blow in the appropriate device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the Attorney General’s Office, according to which it will be a one-year pilot project.
The purpose of this project is the reintegration of the driver, since this will have to attend a rehabilitation course on the road.
In addition to the General Prosecutor’s Office for Road Safety, the General Directorate of Traffic (DGT) and the Foundation Technological Institute for Automobile Safety (FITSA) will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of drivers reported more than once for drunk driving then return to driving the car.
The alkock would avoid it, because it is a vehicle-connected system that measures the rate of alcohol in the exhaust air and prevents the car from starting if the driver is not blowing, or when a higher concentration of alcohol is detected than allowed.
The cost is more than 1000 euros and would be at the expense of the sanctioned.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with such devices allow to reduce up to 65% of the infringements committed during the first year of introduction.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to curb these behaviors before they become criminal offenses.
And to facilitate its development, since the legal reform can be carried out in an ordinary way, and, undoubtedly, the reform necessary for the criminal procedure would require an organic law.
However, the device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been experimentally introduced in some industrial and public vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative of the PSOE in which it is proposed to install this system in school buses, as has already been done in France.
