Talking in sleep
Some children talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the previous day, but to those children who talk while staying asleep.
The first time it happens, at most you get a scare, but in reality it does not matter much.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called somniloquial.
It manifests itself with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Certainly, most of you have been told that you spoke in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in a lifetime, for example associated with an episode of high fever) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child remembers nothing anymore.
There is no single reason that can explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes they are episodes related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, nighttime enuresis (doing pee in bed), or sleepwalking, but not necessarily so.
As already mentioned above, it can be associated with very high fever stages, situations of stress or overexcitement.
In any case, it is a phenomenon still little studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks in a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (crying, shouting, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be advisable to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to check if there is any question that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as a result of the situation.
We have said that it is a benign alteration therefore there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or stress situation).
What can be done, however, is to take into account a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excessively excite the child before going to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid programs or television series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is exhausting to relax, you can use relaxation techniques to help them gain some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more peacefully.
Once the sleepyheads appear try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything of what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not aware of what is happening, and you would interrupt his sleep.
Although he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if it appears very anxious and the episodes have a certain frequency, it is better to consult a doctor or check where such a great anxiety in the child comes from.
If you understand what he’s saying (which isn’t the most common situation), don’t fall into the temptation to interrogate him for information.
You will get nothing, because he is asleep and therefore not conscious to organize his thought.
In addition, you are able to hear what he is saying but not see what he is dreaming to say, so you need to pay close attention to the interpretation of the information and the conclusions to which it could lead.
Never tell your child that you could ask them questions during the night to know their secrets.
Not even for a joke.
This kind of thing causes a lot of anxiety.
In short, don’t worry, it’s nothing serious, it’s an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
