The meeting - The blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it has regained public trust, seriously shaken by the blood scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such drama and popular protests, the Government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, directed by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the recurrence of such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was late in drawing up a report, some provinces set up a committee with the goal of designing a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and two territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, only 38% of people said that they still had confidence in the donation system in Quebec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve the safety of blood samples and field research over the next few years, we have regained public confidence,” she explains before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Quebec’s population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases of the human variant of the mad cow in Europe, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the woman who has been in the presidency since 1998, the year of its foundation.
“And we didn’t know at all if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It was therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which when you have doubts and could achieve a serious disease, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are taken.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980 was refused.
Now, for a few years, it has been shown that without any doubt this disease is transmitted through infected blood.
This episode showed us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle.”
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow to recognize directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus and not that of antibodies against it, on which instead the tests used until then were based.
The TANs allowed to reduce the window period, i.e. from the time the person contracted the disease to the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
That period could be reduced to less than a week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and not being able to identify them is thus greatly reduced.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, this means that it will be necessary to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone is infected with the HIV virus.
As Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted with a transfusion is detected.
I believe that today one can feel at ease in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, says the head of the Héma-Québec management.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
You have to be constantly vigilant,” continues Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to having safe resources, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient resources.
“Needs increase as the population ages.
Being the most aggressive cancer care, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for the number of donors, which on average makes up only 3% of the inhabitants of Quebec acceptable as donors."
However, all healthy people who have reached the age of 18 and meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the latter is widespread, they will be rejected for a period of one year.
“With this 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
Cases of shortage are very rare.
But we need to renew the members of this group of donors as they get older and can no longer make donations.
Now it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to hold them back and encourage them to become regular donors.
Nowadays, life is so hectic that it is difficult to find an hour to donate blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec distributes not only blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited with Héma-Québec, which runs the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, abundant blood rich in stem cells can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the entry into the bank of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to take more than a thousand each year.
You should start proposing them for transplants at the beginning of next year,” says Dr. Décary, who describes this practice of cord blood collection as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they can't access it," because Héma-Québec doesn't have the means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
