If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is first and foremost to the public that it should present its own view of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold works, in Canada the debates are usually held with an exchange of views and not with a bang.
It would therefore be sufficient for the society to open its books, its documents, and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of teams of independent researchers who could shed light on the issue.
