In a democratic system, even deniers have the right of speech.
What Barrack Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Canada Black does so primarily because it rejects the brutal means adopted by the mining company.
This audience is ready to listen to Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civil exchanges of opinion, and not in the perspective of what many perceive as a kind of jamming (researching the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just given the authors of Canada Black an ultimatum urging them to suspend the partilization)
Beyond Garver’s surreal discourse, the Barrack Gold grievance constitutes a direct attack on the freedom of university research and the pursuit of truth, indispensable in any democratic society.
