If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and discuss uncomfortable topics to the richest companies in the world, woefully multiple grievances, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following scientific standards as the authors of Canada Black do.
You have the right to reply.
For a long time, the university environment, of which we are a part, has been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
The excessive measures of Barrick Gold clearly show that, contrary to its claims, it does not seek a transparent debate at all.
