The psychology of bidding in excess: why spend more money?
At auctions, buyers are likely to spend more, to overvalue the goods.
Neurologists and economists researchers at the University of New York have managed to discover the neuro-economic basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, men do not want to stay behind in a race such as the eBay auction, so they are available to pay even a higher price.
Research has sought to trace the nervous pattern of this "match" at the nervous system level through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lot, the other group of players participated in an auction while using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method they examined the active brain areas of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games the participants could win money, but in the auction game, where the substantial element is to bid more than the other, the striated body under the cerebral cortex intensively comes into operation when you lose to the game.
This area of the brain, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the "self-gratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price increase is explained by scanning the vehement reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the economists of the research group conducted a financial tracking survey.
In this investigation, three groups tendered against a partner under different conditions.
They reported to the control group how much the actual value of the product in question was and they made their bet.
To another group besides this they promised that in case of winning they will receive another prize of 15 dollars.
The third group would receive $15 before the auction, but the members of the group would lose the money in the event of a loss at the auction.
The difference between the two groups was that for one of them the win was emphasized, while for the other the loss.
Checking the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the group that played "against loss" were willing to make higher stakes of the control group or "winning".
“These results are not deducible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
In fact, they have so far explained the phenomena that can be found at auctions with the joy of winning and avoiding risk.
Only the methods of creating the neurological image helped to resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so we came up with a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at the University of New York's School of Economics.
Hepatitis: when to go to the doctor?
Nearly half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver diseases are mentioned among the first causes of death.
In Hungary, the number of patients with hepatitis amounts to one hundred thousand, of which only 7000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know that they are infected.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name of infectious liver diseases caused by several viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical are hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the food channel (e.g. water and infected food), hepatitis B, C, D and other blood viruses and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal discharge, saliva).
For those who travel, it is useful to get vaccinated against virus A and B, there is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain, and nausea.
After yellow spots form on the skin and on the whites of the eyes, the stool becomes clear and dark urine, healing occurs within two to three weeks.
One million people die each year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason is, according to estimates, that only one in ten people receives a drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver cancers.
Most infected people do not know that they have contracted the disease because pathogens subtly destroy liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent and perform regular medical tests.
This disease is much more common than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
In the world today, the number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Since even a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease it is worth turning to the family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated by the body, so the infectious power ceases and the formation of tumors can be prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 around the world by patient associations.
The aim is to draw attention to viral chronic hepatitis, the causes of its development and early recognition of the disease.
Who believes in God feels less pain?
According to the result of a recent investigation, religious faith functions as a kind of painkiller that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at the University of Oxford have conducted an interesting experiment, examining how faith in God affects the feeling of pain, the Telegraph reported.
As part of the somewhat bizarre investigation, an electroshock was carried out on 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists, while all were observing a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
Based on the results, Catholic believers were able to reject much of the pain.
Thanks to the human brain’s exploratory technique, it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for pain control.
The test is the first in a series of research in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the University take part in addition to academics.
The test was carried out exactly like this: an instrument that emits discharges and passes the electroshock was connected to the left hand of the subject of the experiment.
The researchers asked participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the 17th century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with Leonardo da Vinci's hermitage painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary originated a kind of religious state among believers, while Leonardo's picture was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and they considered it to be a calming effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and during this time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while observing either the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics reported that the vision of the Virgin Mary made them feel "safe", as if "someone took care" of them and "they calmed down and were pervaded by peace".
Looking at the religious-themed image they realized 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo’s work in front of them.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the test, believes that such a result can be achieved with any image with a strong effect even for atheists, but you need to find the right image.
“We need to look for an image towards which they feed very positive feelings, such as a mother or a father,” the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright was pleased with the result of the research.
“The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it can change our personality,” Wright added.
After the excellent results only the question remains whether the painting of a Madonna by Leonardo or another painter of similar caliber is presented to believers, what effect could it have on the control of pain?
Would the vision of a quality Virgin Mary bring better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On the tenth birthday, Google can claim to be both in people’s pockets and in the sky above their heads; it knows where they spent their holidays, what outpatients they attend and what interests them.
However, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company’s directors, this is still not enough.
What concerns skeptics who make a comparison with the Orwellian nightmare, they do not really see the substance of web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main goal is to collect as much personal data as possible from its users and this is necessary to meet the original goal of Google’s founders that was: “Let’s put all the information in the world into one system!”
According to the director of Google interviewed, the company, after 10 years of revolutionary work, is still at the beginning of being able to manage all the information.
When asked what will happen in five years, Schmidt replied: he would like Google to know how to answer questions like “what do I do tomorrow?” or “what would be the right job for me?”, but the software doesn’t know how to answer seemingly simple questions because it doesn’t know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that during their searches on the Internet exactly the words searched are recorded, from which IP address are searched and on which page the interested parties stop after the search.
With the Personalized Search launched two years ago, users can, for example, store their browsing history, they can relate to what they have searched and clicked, these then in the long run will generate much better tailor-made results; on this same logic it is based Recommendations with which the system offers us products and services based on our previously declared and registered preferences.
What happens if my data is used against me, if they look at what I do? - you ask concerned users of the data monopoly of Google.
In most cases, the Internet users’ counter-reactions are caused by the fear felt for the size of the potential power represented by the company, and not for the sense of guilt, for the fear of punishment, for the desire for freedom, or even for rebellion to power.
However, one fact is confirmed and that is that all the expressions sought are not only recorded but in motivated cases can also be provided to third parties, in such legal cases nothing defends the personal rights of Internet users.
Perhaps the most striking example of this in recent times has been the coordinated action against pedophiles in Brazil, in which Google forwarded to the Brazilian government the information that made it possible to identify pedophiles from the Orkut community page maintained by Google.
Internet users concerned about personal rights instead sighed for relief in May when the company - in agreement with the electronic legal protection association EFF - successfully proved the truth in court against the FBI: even later you can not force Google with any point of the constitution to provide any information requested secretly by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully ripped off nearly 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search expressions obtained in reference to the confirmation of the child protection law passed years earlier, but still failed to get the search lists of individual users and the entire list of web pages and keywords dating back two months.)
Google’s judgment is therefore rather contradictory: those who are afraid of providing their personal data to Google because they believe that this will affect their privacy and privacy by starting to use its services and rise up with the rebellion against the multinationals that stand out for the conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and the proliferation of enthusiasts, activists and computer users who have appeared in numerous countries see in them the future generation of large companies, the "cool corporation", unlike their rival, Microsoft liquidated as the conqueror of the world because of Windows, although both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for an identification code, does not ask for money for its services, the source code is always kept up to date and the program package is much more accessible, youthful and cool than the official practice of the software giant.
But it can also happen because geeks see exactly the problematic relationship between personal rights and the internet, which implies precisely one of the most repeated keywords in recent years, web 2.0.
Web 2.0 speaks only of collaboration, of intentionally leaving traces behind us and exploiting the communication channels at our disposal and while the size of these changes for each individual, the substance is the same: to show ourselves.
A young average can create profiles in multiple community pages, from Facebook to Shanghai, can connect them with other services such as Twitter or last.fm that lists his musical tastes, all of these can insert them into systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, can also write blogs on which his latest photo galleries appear automatically on Click.
Meanwhile, we read of numerous exemplary cases from which it is clear that the girl, seeing the series of photos taken in the morning by the common round of friends, comes to know easily with whom she spent the night her perfidious boyfriend or a company can fire an employee because she wrote a sincere opinion on the summit is a business case:
Those who live an online life do so to show themselves and so we can formulate the fundamental thesis that hides behind the behavior of young people.
Those who want to hide something or just want to avoid the monopoly of Google can do so (starting, for example, with Scroogle using the Google search system but at the same time does not voluntarily leave traces).
There are not a few people who do not sign up for community pages to not be found, Google’s online applications, from word processing to image management and news gathering, can be replaced with alternative versions not linked to huge server parks and that do not make up our best profile yet.
Public opinion is not waiting so long in secret for the moment when Google will pull out the claws.
Currently, the company with its 156 billion dollars worth is worth more than IBM (140 billion dollars), Intel (124 billion dollars) or Coca Cola (110 billion dollars), advertising spaces AdWords/AdSense threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, the services introduced in record time not only cause Microsoft great problems.
However, the critical observers next to all this find alarming points: the corporate leadership, for example, has completely rejected the protest of the employees after having doubled the right of the corporate asylum, has considered too expensive the repeated catering to the daily pleasure of the employees, but all this diminishes in the face of the fact that in 2006 the government of Google has abdicated.
A rule of the company seems to be not to advertise a new service in advance but only when it will be usable, one thing is for sure, however, that our foreseeable problems in the coming months and years we will move the world to one point: while some believe that the project of scanning and storing Google books and magazines will assume such proportions that the company will soon face problems with our health care system.
The fact that Google is building a genetic database can offer good material to the next generation of science fiction writers, the story Scroogled by the famous Cory Doctorow describes the future with Orwellian accents, in which a man with Google data can be approached alarmingly.
