Intelligent machine imitates the flight of the squid
What could be the best way to develop collision avoidance technologies if not mimicking the sensors of obstacles found in nature?
For example, bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the calibres gave Nissan engineers the initial strategic clue on how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotic minicar equipped with bee properties, with the ultimate goal of creating a system capable of scanning all collisions.
Flying bees form their own personal oval space that really looks very much like our protective shield - explained at the exhibition Kazuhiro Doi, director of the PR technology and research and development sector.
Important is the role of the bee's sight, capable of a view of 300 degrees in each direction.
Engineers have drawn on the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the bee's sight.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two metres away within a 180-degree radius, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that instantly turns it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels of the necessary measure to avoid the accident.
This maneuver of avoidance, in a different way from the current system, takes place entirely instinctively.
“If it weren’t for the robot car, it wouldn’t be able to react quickly to avoid collisions,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the innermost and most damaging layer of the protective shield, within which collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid the other bees.
This process must take place at a glance.
But unlike bees, the deviation cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steering of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to scan the other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lithium polymer batteries, lighter and with high energy density, which means that they last longer than lithium ions.
According to Andoh, it is important the instantaneousity of the intelligent reaction, not the processing of the data or even less the ability to store them.
This robot must process some inputs in a few seconds and react.
No need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so use only a memory of a few tens of Kb.
There is no need for a gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that, according to Nissan, within 10 years can be installed on standard vehicles.
Additional application possibility can be represented by unification with the GPS satellite navigation system that avoiding the obstacles present on the road leads to destination.
