Listening to high-volume music for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing injuries.
This is what the European Commission reports, which in a statement issued in Brussels cites the opinion of the EU's Scientific Committee on Emerging and Newly Identified Health Risks (CSRSERI), published today.
"From this scientific opinion, it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable musical devices weekly for more than an hour a day while keeping the device high volume risk a permanent loss of hearing ability."
“I’m concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and cell phones at high acoustic levels can unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably,” says Meglena Kuneva.
"From scientific findings - continues the EU responsible - a clear risk emerges and we must react quickly.
Most importantly, we need to raise awareness among consumers and make this information public.
We also need to re-examine the existing control systems, in the light of this scientific opinion, to ensure that they are fully effective and keep up with the new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the large use of portable musical instruments and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they caused.
"Scientists confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now, together with Member States and stakeholders, examine what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from noise exposure from portable musical instruments and related equipment."
Currently, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music equipment to 100 dB, but concerns are growing about the hearing damage that can result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
You can greatly limit these damages by resorting to solutions such as reducing levels and duration of exposure to noise.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee points out that users of portable music equipment if they listen to high volume (more than 89 decibels) music for only 5 hours per week exceed the limits currently in force regarding the maximum noise allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after a period of 5 years.
This would affect 5-10% of users of such devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
