The Elites in Danger
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the $700 billion bailout plan launched by the White House: a significant portion of Americans were, and are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
The New York Times confirmed yesterday that the current crisis is splitting the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, supportive of federal institutions and the business community, and its new conservative soul, hostile to the "Washington ones" and the world of finance, strong especially in the Central and Southern states.
The soul, by the way, which became prepotently alive with the vote that I said at the beginning.
But this is only an example of the changes, of the great changes, which the current economic earthquake may be predicting or already showing: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not even here.
In both the US and Europe, the crisis seems to be accelerating long-standing incubation phenomena that in the new climate are solidifying and finally coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary re-launch, of the dual state-sovereignty category in relation to a kind of re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking and financial institutions that have, yes, close ties with abroad, but that first of all see involved to a very large extent the budgets of people and families living in one country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears worldwide economically but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems to be essentially out of the question or not to have much to say: the glaring proof is given by the European Union which, as usual, divides itself between different interests and between different state strategies, fails to decide any common political line.
And so it is from the government of each individual state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and relaunch plans, new rules, and above all the provision of funds: since when you get to the straits are only the states that possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources can try to put things back in order.
And they also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, of which probably no market and no international organization will ever be able to dispose to a similar extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the state-national element is also in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that the most recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had entered the realm of the net, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized that our future will instead have to reckon increasingly with those very little material things.
All things that, looking a little, can certainly be transported from one place to another of the earth but are still absolutely linked to a confined space, to a territory.
So those who find themselves to be sovereign, certainly have many more cards than those who are not, those who have the misfortune of living in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty that predicts a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the request of someone who knows how to take over the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, especially economic ones, so inadequate and full of shadow areas.
And at the same time something even deeper and in a certain sense disturbing: a discredit, an insufferability, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in a growing number of Western countries.
That is to say, the belief that before their actions are the same ideas of the hitherto rising social elites, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall sense of the term, to have made their own time and to be increasingly alien to the opinions of the majority seems to be gaining ground.
The demand for leadership, in short, feeds underground a branched but powerful movement of delegitimization of the American ruling classes and traditional political structures, which manifests itself in the sudden "electoral revolts" or in the sudden executions of the collective moods of recent and recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the rise of the conservatives in Austria-Bavaria.
One has the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rituals, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats would say someone, make it increasingly difficult to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not now taking shape in the deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis is intensifying.
In the face of all this, talking about a “rebellion of the masses” on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes wide open certainly isn’t for nothing.
