It’s OpenOffice.org 3.0, the open source personal productivity suite that aims to reach more and more users, from home to office, from professionals to public administration, as a free alternative to the best-known Microsoft Office.
After nearly a year of work by volunteer developers, who oversee SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office is shown to the general public with several new features: to the welcome screen and the revised and rendered interface less spartan, more substantial ones are added such as native compatibility for the standard Apple Mac OS X operating system and support for the new Format 1.
Attention also paid to interoperability with the 2007 Office suite, Open Office is able to open documents with the new Microsoft extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx).
Interesting some features specific to some modules such as the one that allows you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, useful for example to send them by e-mail, or the possibility to import PDF files into the graphic processing form, while retaining the original appearance of the page.
You can also create "hybrid PDF" documents on this front, which accumulate the typical Adobe format graphics with the elements of a spreadsheet or a word processor.
Collaboration is an element that has received several improvements within the applications: in the spreadsheet you can intervene multiple hands between different users, avoiding conflicts on changes, in the word processor, each collaborator is assigned a color in the comments for better recognition during revision.
Some companies are also working to bring some OpenOffice features to the Web (on the cloud, on the cloud), and in the coming weeks they are expected to release the final result.
The Italian version can be downloaded at http://en.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html and added to the English version that was on the mirrors since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, as usual, the suite is also available for the Linux operating system.
On request, the installation CD can also be sent to your home or workplace.
And if the theme of gratuity can be a drag for diffusion in homes, it is precisely in business that the Open Office suite tries the big bet, already being able to count on several projects realized in the public administration and in schools.
And there is no shortage of companies that offer an ideal training, advice and assistance service for small and medium-sized companies, which could open up business prospects.
Open Office consists of five main modules: Writer, for the corresponding videowriting of Word; Calc, is the spreadsheet that aims to replace Excel; Impress, for the PowerPoint emulsifier presentations; Dbase, as in the case of the most famous Access is the program that allows you to work on the databases; Draw, is finally the graphical module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads, and considering that today we are at almost 3 million and 600 thousand, with the release of the new version it is likely that you can also exceed the expected figure.
