Students victims of expensive-rents up to 900 euros for a room
The student housing market is not in crisis.
According to the latest Sunia survey, the tenants’ union, taking a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now taken on very serious characters to the point of excluding entire bands of young people from the right to study for the very high overall costs that the families of origin should bear - explains the head of the study office of Sunia, Laura Mariani - in these cities the strong demand from students has so distorted the market to trigger a general process of increase".
In most cases, the rental offers then contain a series of violations: free type contracts, unregistered, without a limit of duty, sub-rents connected.
For Sunia, extraordinary measures are needed that, through the revision of the tax, can calm prices.
Looking at the details of the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room you go from a minimum of 650 (Black Bande area) to an average value of 800 (Lambiate area, Udine and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 (Vittoria area).
In Florence a bed costs on average 350/400 euros, a room about 700.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in the areas close to the University, they need 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, from 370 to 500 for a single.
In Rome in areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna) about 600 euros are requested for a single room, 450 for a bed in a double.
Only slightly lower values (550 euros for a single room) in areas close to other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecitt<0xC3><0xA0>).
You save only if you move to peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed and 450 a single in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar areas.
In Naples for a bed you need 300/450 euros, for a room you spend from 400 to 600 euros, with the highest prices in the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari for a bed need 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they have a greater weight in the urban economy.
In cities where the phenomenon of renting to non-EU students is more frequent, such as in Perugia, there is finally another anomaly: the increase of about 25/30% of the canon requested from foreign students compared to that applied to Italians.
Goodbye old cinema Paradise, the cities erase the historic rooms
The historical cinemas close in favor of Multiplex.
“A city without movie theaters is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in large Italian urban centers but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of large multisales and the consequent death by consumption of monosales in the central areas of cities, is one of those events that seem inescapable and incontrovertible to us but also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear are often historical places and full of memory, "it is as if a friend, an acquaintance with whom we have always shared a piece of the road and many emotions, "says the director of Nuovo cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago won Tornatore the Oscar and the Grand Prix of the jury of Cannes, and that told the story of a movie for the audience.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of the performers, speak clearly: in the last five years they have closed the doors of 316 cinemas of the traditional type, and to pay the highest price are the halls in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures is Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost monosala cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to demonstrate that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the largest number of new multi-room cinemas: 195 additional screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
“The Italian exercise has developed irrationally,” observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, “it is useful to build new structures but it should guarantee the survival of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its visitors are willing to move into multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of funding for the fund in favor of the beneficiaries: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful, from an ethical and moral point of view, that the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector they would need between 16 and 18 million euros a year.”
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about the closures, decided to run to the shelters with the signing of a protocol between the Municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to protect and promote one-room cinemas both in the historic center and on the outskirts.
Among the rules, there are tax relief measures in favor of operators and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for the stop and in some parking lots.
"It is an initiative that I like," observes Giuseppe Tornatore" and I hope that other cities follow the example of Bologna by putting other measures in place.
It is certain, however, that to counter the superpower of multiplexes, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, because the audience today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema in Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradise", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I walk in front of the Rialto or Quirinale of Via Nazionale now closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, not to see the blackened posters from the dust I turn to the other side.
