When the energy is born from the waves, the big ones come down into the field.
It’s an extinct field, occupying more than 70 percent of the planet’s surface and is now being discovered by the world’s major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources they have set eyes on, and now they are trying to get their hands on, colossal like the Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil dropped, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now environmental conditions and the new increase in oil give impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by offshore offshore offshore wind farms.
This amount would be twice the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And there would be more currents and tides.
Colossus on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it seemed a revolutionary step.
Two years later to bet on marine energy are more and more and among these companies have always voted on traditional energy.
“Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies,” a company spokesman for the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, “and is considering cooperating with us.”
The cooperation in question concerns obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, necessary to launch a marine energy exploitation project in Alaska.
This is a good sign, especially considering that it is in Alaska that the United States continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush has launched a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, there are New York’s Verdant Power Inc. and New Jersey’s Ocean Power along the energy path that comes from the sea, and the sums invested so far, though not known in detail, indicate, according to observers, a rising interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts talk about a technology that is still in its infancy, also because marine energy does not escape all doubts about the environmental impact.
For now, plants such as the Portuguese one or some in Scotland are small in size and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
In order to produce energy on a large scale, however, technologies with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the choices are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which causes the buoys to move up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure rotates a turbine that in turn feeds a generator.
Electricity is sent to shore through submarine cables.
For now there are four such plants under design, waiting only for federal approval and part of the energy could serve as a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and parking lot using six underwater turbines in New York’s East River.
The movement of water when there are tides causes the blades of the turbines to spin, creating a rotational movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to take advantage of the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they tell the Institute for Research on Electricity, deserves at this time the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is precisely on the energy of the tides that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others overlooking the coast, have already invested 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and planned investments up to 35 million for 2009.
